<subSubSection id="28479EE5CC0DC72F25E00EF5F0EE44DD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="C08B890E867EBE61814AD395B3A8F084" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C7B0A51C85AFC678506F9A7F496B98AE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Adults of 
<taxonomicName id="3FB6A380296D86160B87D8054B918C39" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. meihuai" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="meihuai">
<emphasis id="BD5B02C6AE0E64BFB61D5EA2E4C9585F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. meihuai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="D448C3B05C7296044C563897D35741B8" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. igai" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="igai">
<emphasis id="E5924C37A6488234FC67453DE82D5005" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. igai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kimoto in body sizes and color patterns (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="BCF25880DE1B009A8C4A2B426BEFB3DE" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta alishanensis sp. nov., P. igai Kimoto, and P. meihuai sp. nov. on host plant A mature larva of P. alishanensis sp. nov. B adult of P. alishanensis sp. nov. C mature larva of P. igai D adult of P. igai E mature larva of P. meihuai sp. nov. F adult of P. meihuai sp. nov." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545547" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">17D, F</figureCitation>
), but differ by the shining, smooth pronotum and elytra (rough pronotum and elytra covered by reticulate microsculpture in 
<taxonomicName id="EA0B5FC84FE9EB290407310CC172ED96" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. igai" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="igai">
<emphasis id="43F3AF6DD75C459B525179D1960E9F08" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. igai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). In males of 
<taxonomicName id="59D7088223A275F0F70E2C51A19A9C58" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. meihuai" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="meihuai">
<emphasis id="0C7D7F7DC1FF38BE58F2E89FDC6BA977" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. meihuai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., the lanceolate aedeagus (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="19BF5386A6DA453D1D96FB6B563FEF3F" captionStart="Figure 22" captionStartId="F22" captionText="Figure 22. Diagnostic characters of Pyrrhalta meihuai sp. nov. A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E abdominal ventrite VIII F gonocoxae G spermatheca H abdominal ventrite V, female I abdominal ventrite V, male." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure22" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545552" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">22C</figureCitation>
) is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="B59CE0634C021D1E7362CEAEDCA29022" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. alishanensis" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="alishanensis">
<emphasis id="CA90EE15DF42F09D03D73352E75C8F11" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. alishanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9E194C86BFCFE3D358E2B3B6F4C8734D" captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Diagnostic characters of Pyrrhalta alishanensis sp. nov. A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E abdominal ventrite VIII F spermatheca G abdominal ventrite V, female H abdominal ventrite V, male I gonocoxae." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545546" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">16C</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="F97ACA24A684A1CF84EF49BF6F28A70F" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. meifena" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="meifena">
<emphasis id="EA0681173AD83B27CF8292EC4635F060" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. meifena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6D21E08F50A8A6C00745F23B2F7250CA" captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Diagnostic characters of Pyrrhalta meifena Kimoto A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E abdominal ventrite VIII F spermatheca G abdominal ventrite V, female H abdominal ventrite V, male I gonocoxae." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545550" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">20C</figureCitation>
) but differs in possessing one secondary endophallic sclerite in addition to the primary endophallic sclerite (no secondary sclerite in 
<taxonomicName id="EED6CF69F1E68FAC150A3EC79D6A2BB3" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. meifena" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="meifena">
<emphasis id="21E6DB53993BCB3435FDE45040BE5EB6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. meifena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; two secondary sclerites in 
<taxonomicName id="89F4AF243F10C54CF1E3003914485887" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. alishanensis" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="alishanensis">
<emphasis id="9FC0C94DF5BCBC16F0245BC35E7B0310" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. alishanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EFAB1D33A36A02D48D2B21AD94E951CC" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="host">
<paragraph id="2129F3F5922A47584EDAEAB889293CAB" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Host plant.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="20E98FA3F926C3698C5A6A1ED9E1EBCD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Larvae and adults feed on leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="DC0084A9095AAC54EF153B15C6359E35" authorityName="Hayata" authorityYear="1911" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Acer" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Acer serrulatum" order="Sapindales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="serrulatum">
<emphasis id="A1A25A2FBD355F649B53D916345F877F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Acer serrulatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hayata (
<taxonomicName id="FE9FE5D8A6B05C48BDECD6D5AB169D24" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Acer" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Sapindales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Sapindaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="608CB6E3D7E764577BF7F72FEFB757FD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="2DB608CFD3D872E2A463AD0377A8F0D8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9C970671DA0A2AE669BCFA2A65E7DB99" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Mr Mei-Hua Tsou collected mature larvae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="FAE4CF7090E5EB3D1A7CD7B298F7FC83" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Diagnostic characters of Pyrrhalta viridipennis Kimoto A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, from Alishan (阿里山), dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E apex of aedeagus, from Shihfen (十分), dorsal view F ditto, lateral view G apex of aedeagus, from Hsiangyang, dorsal view H ditto, lateral view I abdominal ventrite VIII J gonocoxae K abdominal ventrite V, female L abdominal ventrite V, male M apex of tibia of middle leg N spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545544" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">14E</figureCitation>
) April 5, 2009 in Mingchi, Northeast Taiwan. They began burrowing into soil at the same day, and built underground chambers for pupation. Duration of the pupal stage was 24-27 days. adults (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="10071E1AF7D6DE3067475F042427DFDA" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta alishanensis sp. nov., P. igai Kimoto, and P. meihuai sp. nov. on host plant A mature larva of P. alishanensis sp. nov. B adult of P. alishanensis sp. nov. C mature larva of P. igai D adult of P. igai E mature larva of P. meihuai sp. nov. F adult of P. meihuai sp. nov." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545547" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">17F</figureCitation>
) appeared from spring to summer.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8EDCB583EC49B20983CA3C8FC9C5CC1C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="FD7C1C142F5457BCD1393D09F9C3D97E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3AC7DC32CEA36BC0B449EE908E7B8B65" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">The species is widespread at mid-altitudes (1,500-2,500 m) in Taiwan.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3FB95DD4D3708894D2CB7C13458577F9" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="B8C12D0FE29F858E97467EC9FECF410F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="99A62B1609578FE283397EAD206F80F8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Dedicated to Mr. Mei-Hua Tsou. He, the first author, and Mr. Hou-Jay Chen were the first to collect larvae of this new species and rear them successfully to adults.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
